post_text: Sackets Harbor CSD is revamping the drive-through format for our Open House because of the possibility of inclement weather. We are now having a walk-through experience. The times for visiting our school remain the same. Kindergarten through Grade 2 should arrive anytime between 5 PM and 6 PM and Grades 3-5 should arrive anytime between 6 PM - 7 PM. Families with elementary children can enter the doors by the elementary loop and can move through our hallways to pick up needed forms and meet teachers as you walk by. Traffic will move in one direction. The times for Grades 6-8 still remain from 5 PM - 6 PM and Grades 9-12 will be from 6 PM - 7 PM and will be in our gymnasium. Again, foot traffic will flow in one direction only. Please enter our gym lobby and proceed to the gymnasium to pick up needed forms, schedules, and greet teachers. We look forward to seeing many of you tonight!

post_text:
Hello SHCS Community,

We just learned that the YMCA will be making a decision about running their childcare/learning center programs by August 25th. This includes both the M/T/R/F after-school program (2:00 PM - 6:00 PM) as well as the Wednesday all-day program (6:30 AM - 6:00 PM). The YMCA will be making these determinations based on how many families register. It was communicated to the YMCA that we have ~20 families interested in both programs based on the survey results so far. If you intend to have your child/ren participate in the YMCA's after-school or all-day programs, please call or email Amelia Nakano at the YMCA (anakano@nnyymca.org or 315-755-2005) as soon as possible. If you have any questions, please refer to the District's FAQ or call/email us at SHCSD. Thank you!

post_text:
Happy Friday Sackets Harbor!

Ms. Gaffney and Mrs. Horack will host another Town Hall forum on Thursday, August 20, 2020 at 6:00 PM. This will be held BOTH in-person and virtually. For those of you who wish to join us in-person, we invite you into our gymnasium. Guests may enter our gym lobby and proceed directly into the gymnasium. Everyone joining us must wear a mask until they are seated. Here is the link for the virtual connection: https://youtu.be/4woWdmksxBU

Topics to be covered at this Town Hall include: a showing of a video detailing some of the changes our school community should expect, a brief introduction to Parent Square which is the web-based program our community will use to send screening results, a brief training on recognizing the signs and symptoms of COVID-19, and we will address any questions.

Don't forget to complete your Reopening Survey. It's due on Monday and is desperately needed for our continued planning. Thank you!

post_text: Thank you to Rickey and Sarah Martin, along with their children, for the generous donations to support Sackets Harbor Central School District's reopening efforts! The monetary donation will help us purchase a software to track required health screenings and produce a video to help our school community transition back to school comfortably. The disposable masks will come in handy when students forget their cloth masks and the mounted touchless thermometers for our entry ways will make entering our school building much more efficient. Thank you so much for supporting the health and safety of the faculty, staff, students, and entire community of Sackets Harbor Central School District. #patriotsperservere

Good afternoon SHCS Community,
The Governor is permitting all school districts in NYS to reopen.

This is a reminder that the Sackets Harbor Central School Administration will be rolling out the entire Reopening Plan on Wednesday, August 12, 2020 at 6:00 PM. This will be presented virtually in real-time and will cover a variety of topics including the school's schedule, health and safety policies and procedures, transportation, food service, technology, special education, communication mechanisms, etc... The link to access this session can be found below. Questions or suggestions pertaining to our school district's reopening can be submitted via the link below. We ask that you wait until we present the reopening plan before you submit questions as we are hopeful that most of your questions will be answered during this Virtual Town Hall session. We look forward to collaborating with all of you to ensure a successful reopening!

https://youtu.be/0Zq1XusxtvQ

post_text:
The Class of 2020 received a beautiful tribute today from Fort Drum's Combat Aviation Brigade. A flag was donated in the name of our Class of 2020. This flag was flown on a UH-60-60M Army Blackhawk helicopter, tail number 92-26446, over Afghanistan, during Combat Operations in support of Operation Freedom's Sentinel of May 10, 2020. This flag symbolizes the sovereign power of the United States of America and the unshakable resolve and dedication of the men and women of the United States Army to defend freedom wherever it is threatened. Thank you, Combat Aviation Brigade for the gift and thank you for your service.

This flag will be displayed at our upcoming graduation events on Wednesday night and will also be flown at the annual Veterans Day Ceremony which will be held in November 2020.

post_text: The Governor's Executive Order 202.39, issued on 6/08/2020 indicates that the annual meeting and general election has been changed to 6/16/2020. The process of counting the ballots will begin shortly after 5:00 PM on 6/16/2020. Residents who would like to view the ballot counting process are asked to contact District Clerk, Sheri Rose to obtain the needed link for viewing. Ballots may be dropped off at the elementary entrance near the bus garage today, 6/09/2020 from 10:00 AM - 5:00 PM. This drop-off location will be clearly marked. This is the last opportunity to hand deliver ballots and place them in the ballot box. Ballots delivered by the U.S. Post Office will be accepted through 5:00 PM on 6/16/2020.

post_text: On Wednesday, June 24th, starting at ~6:30 PM, there will be a car parade to honor Sackets Harbor Central School's Class of 2020. Our local police department along with our local fire departments will be leading the way. We would like to encourage school district residents to help honor and celebrate our seniors by coming out on their porches, into their front yards, or at another location to cheer our seniors on as they drive by. Be sure to keep appropriate social distance, of course. Please help us spread the word as we want our entire community to join us in honoring our seniors. We truly appreciate your support!

post_text: Congratulations to Nyah Chiodi!! We are so proud of you!
shared_text:
Jefferson County Sheriff's Office
April 30 at 5:43 PM ·

Earlier this month the Victims Assistance Center of Jefferson County announced an art contest for children of all ages inviting them to draw, color or paint an image representing law enforcement appreciation. The winners’ artwork would be displayed at local Sheriff Offices and Police departments. Today we were thrilled to see the results at the Public Safety Building, framed and ready to display!

Winner, ages 3-5: Leighton Anderson, age 3 (not pictured)
Winner, ages 6-9: Alana Pounds, age 8
Winner, ages 10-14: Nyah Chiodi, age 13
Winner, ages 15-18: Maddy Furhman, age 16

Leighton’s artwork will be displayed at the St. Lawrence County Sheriff’s Office. The other winners, and the artwork of ALL of the other great little artists that submitted entries, will be displayed at the Jefferson County Sheriff’s Office. We appreciate the hard work of all that participated!

This is the last post to wrap up last week's Patriots Pay it Forward Projects. We had so many families share their choices and we are so pleased! Enjoy these:

The Gibeau boys were busy last week planing vegetables and flowers, they made strawberry shortcake for their papa, they made bird feeders, and they surprised their grandmother with flowers and candy on her door step.

The Lennox Family spent some time outside, made some thoughtful crafts, and enjoyed family time!

The Brown Family purchased groceries for a neighbor who cannot be out and about. They also picked up trash on the trail.

Our families did such an amazing job last week! We are proud to be Patriots! #PatriotsPersevere

post_text: What an amazingly interesting few weeks we have had here at Sackets Harbor Central School District. In a matter of days, we have completely revamped the way we do business. From teaching/learning, to food service, to transportation, to every aspect of our organizational operations, we needed to change it all. Our faculty, staff, students, and community have come together to make the impossible possible and it has been so impressive. This is history in the making and we are trying to pause so that we can capture and share some of it. More to come... #Patriotspersevere
text: What an amazingly interesting few weeks we have had here at Sackets Harbor Central School District. In a matter of days, we have completely revamped the way we do business. From teaching/learning, to food service, to transportation, to every aspect of our organizational operations, we needed to change it all. Our faculty, staff, students, and community have come together to make the impossible possible and it has been so impressive. This is history in the making and we are trying to pause so that we can capture and share some of it. More to come... #Patriotspersevere

post_text:
Our meal distribution program will start tomorrow, Friday, March 20, 2020. If you have signed up, you may pick up between the hours of 11:00 AM-12:00 PM or the meals will be delivered between the hours of 10:30 AM - 11:30 AM.

If any family who initially declined, wishes to change their mind, they are welcomed to call Sheryl Crandall at 315-646-3575 or email her at scrandall@sacketspatriots.org at any time. We will gladly add families to our distribution list.

Do not hesitate to reach out to us if you need anything at all. We are all in this together! #PatriotsPersevere

post_text:
Ms. Gaffney, Mrs. Horack, and Ms. Kleiboer are wearing red, not only to celebrate Valentine's Day, but also to raise awareness about a community engagement campaign called #QUITLYING. This campaign is meant to empower kids, schools, and communities to call out JUUL and other e-cigarette companies for their lies about vaping and nicotine addiction.

American Heart Association CEO Nancy Brown says, “E-cigarette companies lie to our kids when they falsely claim their products are safe, and they deceive parents by marketing devices that look like USB drives, pens and eye liner,” Brown said.

We encourage our school community to learn more and join the campaign at QUITLYING.org. #QUITLYING

post_text:
Our first grade students researched a planet and took their facts and wrote a letter to home about their planet. With a little technology they were able to pretend that they were writing from their planet and sharing their experience!

This week they had a planet party to celebrate their success and to watch their " letters from a planet" as a group. Students had fun creating a constellation, tossing " moon rocks", completing space-themed lego challenges, drinking " moon juice" with a side of " Saturn's rings" and more!

Attention Former Sackets Harbor Sentinels:
Would you like a memento from your days of marching for the Sackets Harbor Sentinels? If so, we have a number of old uniforms we are looking to give away rather than simply discarding them. There is so much history in our marching program and we would love to see some of these uniforms appreciated by future generations. post_text:
This week we kick off the Positivity Project with the Other People Matter Mindset. The Other People Matter Mindset means the following. We understand that our words and actions affect others. We cheer others successes. We are present and give others our attention. We support others when they are struggling. And last but certainly not least we identify and appreciate the good in others.

This week we will be talking about how we display the other people matter mindset at school, at home and in our community. Take some time this week to think about how you display the other people matter mindset. #wearesackets #otherpeoplematter

post_text:
Happy Summer SHCS Community!

This is a reminder that our Sackets Harbor Sentinels will be marching on Saturday, July 20th at the CanAm Parade. The parade will begin at noon. It would be great to have many staff, students and families support our music program this weekend. We are looking for students to carry the banner. If interested, please contact Mr. Geraci at jgeraci@sacketspatriots.org.

Student marchers must arrive to SHCS at 10:00 AM for a brief rehearsal. The entrance is located by the gym through the courtyard. There will also be a kickball game for band students versus Indian River CSD immediately following the parade.

We will see you this weekend!

SHCS Music Department

Dear Sackets Harbor Central School Community,

Phase 2 of our Capital Improvement Project is progressing rapidly with work inside and outside the school and we would like to provide an update on access to the building. Starting the week of July 8, access to the school will be very limited. If you have an urgent need to come to the school, please call us beforehand (315-646-3575) to verify the best way to enter the school or to arrange to meet school staff outside the building.

Thank you for your understanding and we apologize for any inconvenience.

post_text: This didn't make our morning announcements today but we wanted to be sure to share the awesome accomplishment of Sackets Harbor student, Anne Tyler. This past weekend, she competed in her first NEIB USA Powerlifting competition in Kingston, NY. She broke three American National records! She deadlifted 213lbs; squatted 145lbs and benched 95lbs. Congrats to Anne! SHCS is proud of you!

post_text:
Students in kindergarten and 3rd grade participated in the Students Rebuild Ocean Challenge! After reading about sea creatures and researching them students took action by creating sea creatures and submitting them to the Students Rebuild Ocean Challenge!

For every sea creature that is submitted to Students Rebuild, the Bezos Family Foundation will make a donation to programs training coastal youth in ocean conservation and coral restoration.

Our students have raised $128 so far and we have until June 8th to keep going. Great job students for taking action and supporting our ocean!

The Neonatal Intensive Care Unit at Samaritan Medical Center received a donation of sewn hearts made by National Junior Honor Society students with the help of retired teachers Brenda Scordo and Chris Reinhardt. These fabric hearts can be used in a program that will help and support mothers who need to be separated from their newborns.

Great job exhibiting the pillar of service!

post_text:
On Thursday, June 6th, 2019 at 6pm in the school gymnasium, the Sackets Harbor Central School District will be inducting four new members into their Athletic Hall of Fame: Donald J. Bachner (special contributor), Jean H. Derouin (athlete), Herbert Huttemann (athlete and coach), and Lynne Burton Morrison (athlete).

The Sackets Harbor community is invited to attend the ceremony that will precede our Spring Sports Banquet and will include a dessert bar. If you plan on attending, please call the main office (315-646-1029) by May 31st to make your reservation. There is no charge to attend, although donations will be accepted to help offset the cost of the event and for future Hall of Fame inductions.

There will also be an informal meet and greet immediately following the induction ceremony at The Sackets Boathouse. Everyone is invited!
